<br>
Wezloc <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uizarek.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Izarek</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#333333>(5/24/02 3:19:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AA ability, dire summoned charm, why not?</span><hr size=1> I'm a little annoyed when VI talks about there not being enough summmoned mobs to make a summoned line of spells available:<br>
<br>
- We have a anti-summon nukes.<br>
- VI chooses how often they add summoned mobs into the game.<br>
- Necros can charm undead.  And although there are more undead mobs, not all zones have them.<br>
- Druids can charm plants.  How many plant mobs are there?  Not many.<br>
- If the frequency of the use of an ability was the determining factor in its existance than Mages wouldn't get Mass Group Buff (usable on 2 spells, both in the same line) and we wouldn't get Turn Summoned.<br>
<br>
Which way is it?  Not enough summoned mobs to justify charm?  Or we have enough summoned mobs to justify Turn Summoned and enough group spells to justify Mass Group Buff?<br>
<br>
I'm not going to bother posting to the official website because they haven't finished caster balancing, and the response is going to be the same as it always has.<br>
<br>
One reason I can think charming summoned mobs hasn't been implemented is because all summoned pets are considered summoned mobs.  But I can't see why that would be a big imbalance since bards and enchanters can charm pets (and actually make them poof)<br>
<br>
Izarek <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umaldisdainatheist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maldisdain Atheist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 69<br> <font color=#333333>(5/24/02 4:18:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dynamic.gamespy.com/~cazic/cazic/ubb/uploads/StaffOfSerpent2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AA ability, dire summoned charm, why not?</span><hr size=1> Actually, the damage output of a DC pet v. the damage output of a mage epic pet (or GVW) is pretty highly variable.  In massive encounters (Tormax/VindiStatue/Idol/AoW), my muzzled, imped, focused, VoGed pet will typically outdamage all other pets by a great margin.  My experience in the few experience groups I've had with Epic magicians is that the magician contributes significantly more damage than my pet does alone (since we often use root to control mob aggro and keep the mob on the epic pet, thus we get the benefit of the 50pt damage shield).<br>
<br>
Even so, I continue to agree that magicians would benefit from a useful pet-enhancing AA.<br>
 <p>
Master Maldisdain Atheist<BR>
